Project - TheraBank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Objective:¶

The project objective is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Domain:¶

Banking

Business Context:¶

This case is about Thera Bank whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Preparing the data to train a model
  • Training and making predictions using a classification model
  • Model evaluation

Dataset Information¶

The dataset contains data on 5000 customThe dataset contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaigners.

Attribute Information:¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer.(in thousand of dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month. (in thousand of dollars)
  • Education: Education Level.
    • 1: Undergrad;
    • 2: Graduate;
    • 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any.(in thousand of dollars)
  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Insights and Summary from Univariate Analysis¶

For the Univariate analysis and based on items computed so far, AND THE GIVEN DATA SET sample, we summarize our insights as follows:

  • There were no null values or missing values as a result of the null check
  • The datatypes for all columns were numerical and no objects or strings were observed. However some of the columns were observed to be binary 1 or 0 which implies these were mapped as ordinals from Yes/No type categorical data.
  • From the description of the dataset using the describe() and the histogram plots above we describe the distribution of the columns and skewness as follwos:

ID:The data distribution is normal with mean and median equal.

Age:The data distribution is uniform with mean and median very close in values

Experience:The data distribution is uniform and has similar characteristics as the Age attribute.

Education: Mean and median is almost equal. Data is uniformly distributed

Income: The data distribution is right skewed with mean greater than median

ZIP Code: the data distribution is slightly left skewed but with relatively narrow range and standard deviation

Family: The distribution has 4 peaks and data suggests inverse relationship between the family number and corresponding number of samples in the dataset.

Personal Loan: approximately 90.6% of the customers did not take out a personal loan

Mortgage: A majority of customers do not have mortgage with the Bank.

Securities Account : Approximately 89.56% did not have a securities account wih the bank

CD account: Approximately 93.96% did not have a CD account with the bank.

Online: slightly higher number of customers use online banking in the sample.

Credit Card: More than twice the number of customers do not use credit card issued by the bank compared to those that use the credit card issued by the bank

In [167]:
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = ["No Loan", "Loan"] , yticklabels = ["No Loan", "Loan"] )
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.show()

In our classifier we have taken the positive class i.e class of interest, which is the acceptance of the personal loan from the bank. For our classifier the confusion matrix enables us to compare the predicted labels from the actual or True labels. With the classifier default threshold of 0.5, the confusion matrix gave the True Positives (TP), False Positives (FP) True Negatives (TN) and False Negatives (FN). The TP = 44, FP = 33, TN = 1318, and FN = 105. We also evaluated the following metrics: Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1 score, and ROC curve including the area under the ROC curve (a_ROC).

  • our model was quite good at predicting the negative class i.e. non acceptance of the personal loan from bank.
  • The Recall and Precision values were good and consistent including the F1 score.

  • The a_ROC suggests our model is better than a random classifier i.e 64% vs 50%.

  • We varied the model Threshold a little bit above and below the threshold. However the Accuracy, Recall,and Precision did not show an improvement.

  • There was some degree of class imbalance so we will put more weight on Recall and Precision metrics rather than the Accuracy measure.

The features we found most important to our classifier were: Income and CCAvg.

Results vs Business Problem¶

In [ ]:
- In this project, the case was  about Thera Bank whose management wanted to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).
- A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. 
- This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

-In summary, the results suggests that our model is a reasonable fit  to the business problem. The model enabled a good 
---- prediction, with good accuracy and performance metrics such as Recall and Precision) for the negative class, customers that do not wish to take a personal loan with the bank. 
---- this in turn can enable us, by default, to have a good understanding of the positive class.
- Our modeling also showed that Income and Cfg were good features to use for targeting customers. 
The zip code data was quite narrow and suggests that the marketing campaign could explore a wider zip code areas.
